  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">How Free Markets Generate Inequality</h2>
    <p>In a free market economy, income is distributed through factor markets — households earn income by supplying land, labour, capital, and entrepreneurship. The <strong>circular flow of income</strong> illustrates this: firms pay wages, rent, interest, and profit to households in return for factor services.</p>
    <p>However, households do not own equal amounts of factors:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Some households own large amounts of capital (shares, property) — they receive high investment income</li>
      <li>Some workers have scarce, highly valued skills — they receive high wages</li>
      <li>Entrepreneurial success generates large profits for some households</li>
      <li>Households with few productive assets or low-skilled labour receive very low incomes</li>
    </ul>
    <p>The market rewards factor ownership — and ownership is very unequally distributed. The result is an unequal distribution of <strong>income</strong> (the flow of earnings) and <strong>wealth</strong> (the stock of assets).</p>

    <div class="key-terms">
      <div class="key-term-card">
        <div class="term">Income inequality</div>
        <div class="definition">Unequal distribution of earnings from labour, capital, land, and enterprise. Measured by flows over a time period (e.g., annual wages).</div>
      </div>
      <div class="key-term-card">
        <div class="term">Wealth inequality</div>
        <div class="definition">Unequal distribution of accumulated assets — property, savings, investments, inheritance. Tends to be more concentrated than income inequality.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3>Why markets do not correct inequality</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Wages reflect productivity and scarcity of skills, not needs — those with low skills or disabilities may earn far below subsistence levels</li>
      <li>Capital and land ownership is self-reinforcing — wealth generates more wealth through investment returns and inheritance</li>
      <li>The price mechanism rations goods to those with willingness and ability to pay — not to those with greatest need</li>
      <li>There is no automatic market mechanism that ensures an equitable distribution of outcomes</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="callout key-term">
      <div class="callout-title">Note</div>
      <p>Inequality is a form of <strong>market failure in equity</strong> — the market may be allocatively efficient (maximising total welfare) yet still produce outcomes that many consider inequitable. This is one justification for government redistribution policies (covered in Unit 3.4).</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="recap">
    <div class="recap-title">Key points to remember</div>
    <ul>
      <li>Free market distributes income through factor markets — wages, rent, interest, profit</li>
      <li>Unequal factor ownership → unequal income and wealth</li>
      <li>Income inequality = unequal earnings flow; wealth inequality = unequal asset stock</li>
      <li>Markets reward productive ownership, not need</li>
      <li>No automatic market mechanism ensures equity</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="tab-content" id="practice-2-12">
  <div class="callout remember">
