  <div class="exercises">
    <div class="exercises-title">Practice Questions <span class="hl-badge">HL</span></div>

    <div class="exercise">
      <div class="exercise-q">1. Using the circular flow of income model, explain why a free market economy tends to generate an unequal distribution of income.</div>
      <details class="answer">
        <summary>Show answer</summary>
        <div class="answer-content">
          In the circular flow, households supply factors of production (land, labour, capital, entrepreneurship) to firms and receive factor payments (rent, wages, interest, profit) in return. Income distribution depends on how much of each factor a household owns and what that factor earns in the market. Households that own large amounts of capital and land receive high investment income; households with scarce, highly productive skills receive high wages; successful entrepreneurs earn large profits. Households with few productive assets or low-skill labour earn little. Since factor ownership is very unequally distributed, the resulting income distribution is also highly unequal — and the market mechanism itself has no mechanism to correct this.
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>

    <div class="exercise">
      <div class="exercise-q">2. Distinguish between income inequality and wealth inequality. Why does wealth inequality tend to be greater than income inequality?</div>
      <details class="answer">
        <summary>Show answer</summary>
        <div class="answer-content">
          <strong>Income inequality</strong> refers to the unequal distribution of earnings over a period of time — wages, salaries, dividends. <strong>Wealth inequality</strong> refers to the unequal distribution of accumulated assets — property, financial investments, savings, and inheritance. Wealth inequality tends to be greater because: (1) wealth accumulates over time from saving high incomes; (2) wealth generates further income (returns to capital), compounding over generations; (3) inheritance transfers wealth from one generation to the next, preserving and amplifying inequality; and (4) those at the bottom of the income distribution have little ability to save, leaving them with minimal wealth.
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

